# UI Styling Theme + Responsiveness

## Color and Theme Rules
- Never use hardcoded colors (`#hex`, `rgb()`, named colors) in UI components.
- Always derive palette from `const theme = useTheme(); const colors = Colors(theme);`.
- Reuse existing keys in `shared-uis/constants/Colors.ts` before adding any new key.
- Add new color keys only when truly required and keep them aligned with the platform's professional visual tone.
- Every new or updated UI must look correct in both light and dark themes.

## Responsive Layout Rules
- Do not use `Dimensions.get("window")` directly inside components for responsive layout.
- If hooks cannot be used (module-level utility code), use `getConstrainedWidth()` / `getConstrainedHeight()` from `shared-libs/contexts/mobile-layout-context.provider.tsx`.

## Styling Structure Rules
- Keep styles in the same file as the component.
- Keep `StyleSheet.create(...)` definitions at the bottom of the file.
- Do not use external stylesheets.
- Do not add inline style objects in JSX.

## Quick Pattern
```tsx
const theme = useTheme();
const colors = Colors(theme);
const styles = useMemo(() => useStyles(colors), [colors]);
```

## Self-Check Before Finishing
- Colors come from `Colors(theme)` tokens.
- Existing tokens were preferred over new token additions.
- UI remains professional and brand-consistent in both themes.
- Styles are colocated, bottom `StyleSheet`, and no inline/external styling.
